###How to fix the Common Vulnerabilities issue of CVE-2021-44790
CVE-2021-44790 is a buffer overflow vulnerability in the mod_lua module of Apache HTTP Server. This vulnerability can be exploited by a remote attacker to execute arbitrary code on the affected system.

To fix this vulnerability, you should upgrade to the latest version of Apache HTTP Server that includes a patch for this vulnerability. You can find the latest version of Apache HTTP Server on the Apache Software Foundation website.

CVE-2021-44790 falls under the OWASP Top 10 Web Application Security Risks category of Injection. Injection flaws occur when unvalidated or malicious data is sent to an interpreter as part of a command or query. The attacker's hostile data can trick the interpreter into executing unintended commands or accessing data without proper authorization.

Here are some additional steps you can take to protect your Apache HTTP Server from this vulnerability:

* Enable the mod_security module. This module provides a variety of security features, including protection against injection attacks.
* Use a web application firewall (WAF) to filter out malicious traffic. A WAF can help to prevent attackers from exploiting vulnerabilities in your web server.
* Keep your Apache HTTP Server software up to date. Software updates often include security patches that can help to protect your system from known vulnerabilities.

By following these steps, you can help to protect your Apache HTTP Server from the CVE-2021-44790 vulnerability and other security threats.
